00:02:01.510 --> 00:02:03.060
So, let's go through this one.

00:02:03.060 --> 00:02:10.070
So, what we're saying is that
we have n equals to 4, and m

00:02:10.070 --> 00:02:12.960
sub I being equal
to negative 2.

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:16.000
If we have n equals 4, what
is the highest value of

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:17.780
l that we can have?

00:02:17.780 --> 00:02:18.350
STUDENT: 3.

00:02:18.350 --> 00:02:18.620
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:02:18.620 --> 00:02:22.260
We can have n 4, l 3, and then,
sure, we can have m sub

00:02:22.260 --> 00:02:26.430
l equal negative 2 if l equals 3
What's the second value of l

00:02:26.430 --> 00:02:27.260
that we can have?

00:02:27.260 --> 00:02:28.670
2.

00:02:28.670 --> 00:02:29.140
OK.

00:02:29.140 --> 00:02:32.920
So we can have this
orbital here.

00:02:32.920 --> 00:02:36.930
What about l equals 1,
can we have this?

00:02:36.930 --> 00:02:37.870
No, we can't.

00:02:37.870 --> 00:02:42.110
Because if l equals 1, we can
not have m sub l equal

00:02:42.110 --> 00:02:45.160
negative 2, right, because the
magnetic quantum number only

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:49.010
goes from negative l
to positive l here.

00:02:49.010 --> 00:02:52.000
So that means it's not possible,
if we've made these

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:54.870
stipulations in the first
place, to have a case

00:02:54.870 --> 00:02:56.450
where l equals 1.

00:02:56.450 --> 00:02:59.220
So this means we can only have
2 different values of l.

00:02:59.220 --> 00:03:02.270
We already know our
value of m.

00:03:02.270 --> 00:03:05.730
So now we're just counting up
our orbitals, an orbital is

00:03:05.730 --> 00:03:08.650
completely described by
the 3 quantum numbers.

00:03:08.650 --> 00:03:12.670
So we end up having
2 orbitals here.

00:03:12.670 --> 00:03:18.410
All right, so hopefully if you
