00:05:00.010 --> 00:05:02.390
favorite atoms to talk about,
but it would be nice to get to

00:05:02.390 --> 00:05:05.400
the point of bonding and even
reactions to talk about all

00:05:05.400 --> 00:05:07.570
the exciting things we
can think about once

00:05:07.570 --> 00:05:08.280
we're at that point.

00:05:08.280 --> 00:05:11.050
So, one we finish our discussion
of how we think

00:05:11.050 --> 00:05:16.210
about multi-electron atoms, we
can go right on and start

00:05:16.210 --> 00:05:18.780
talking about these
other things.

00:05:18.780 --> 00:05:24.400
All right.

00:05:24.400 --> 00:05:27.400
So, let's pick up where we left
off, first of all we're

00:05:27.400 --> 00:05:30.470
still on the hydrogen
atom from Monday.

00:05:30.470 --> 00:05:33.260
And on Monday what we were
discussing was the solution to

00:05:33.260 --> 00:05:36.880
the Schrodinger equation
for the wave function.

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:39.930
And we also, when we solved or
we looked at the solution to

00:05:39.930 --> 00:05:43.290
that Schrodinger equation,
what we saw was that we

00:05:43.290 --> 00:05:46.270
actually needed three different
quantum numbers to

00:05:46.270 --> 00:05:48.990
fully describe the wave function
of a hydrogen atom or

00:05:48.990 --> 00:05:51.550
to fully describe an orbital.

00:05:51.550 --> 00:05:54.480
We didn't just need that n, not
just the principle quantum

00:05:54.480 --> 00:05:56.460
number that we needed to discuss
the energy, but we

00:05:56.460 --> 00:05:59.750
also need to talk about l and
m, as we did in our clicker

00:05:59.750 --> 00:06:01.470
question up here.

00:06:01.470 --> 00:06:04.200
We also talked about well, what
is that when we say wave

00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:06.040
function, what does that
actually mean?

00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:09.070
And first we discussed the fact
that well, in terms of a

00:06:09.070 --> 00:06:11.470
classical analogy, we don't
really have one for wave

00:06:11.470 --> 00:06:13.880
function, we can't really think
of a way to picture wave

00:06:13.880 --> 00:06:17.240
function thinking in classical
terms. But we do have an

00:06:17.240 --> 00:06:19.610
interpretation for wave
function squared.

00:06:19.610 --> 00:06:22.280
And when we take the wave
function and square it, that's

00:06:22.280 --> 00:06:24.940
going to be equal to the
probability density of finding

00:06:24.940 --> 00:06:29.000
an electron at some point
in your atom.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:33.000
And that's useful in terms of
seeing a general shape, but if

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:36.060
we're actually interested in
thinking about how far away

00:06:36.060 --> 00:06:38.900
that electron is from the
nucleus, you can see that

00:06:38.900 --> 00:06:41.480
instead of talking about
probability density, which is

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:44.590
the probability per volume,
instead it would be much more

00:06:44.590 --> 00:06:47.400
useful to talk about something
called radial probability

00:06:47.400 --> 00:06:50.460
distribution, or in other
words talking about the

00:06:50.460 --> 00:06:54.030
probability of finding the
electron at some distance,

00:06:54.030 --> 00:06:58.600
which we define as r, from the
nucleus in a spherical shell

00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:02.670
that is just infinitesimally
small, infinitesimally thin at

00:07:02.670 --> 00:07:06.760
distance or at a thickness that
we'll call a d r here.

00:07:06.760 --> 00:07:10.340
So, basically what we're saying
is if we take any shell

00:07:10.340 --> 00:07:13.770
that's at some distance away
from the nucleus, we can think

00:07:13.770 --> 00:07:16.920
about what the probability is of
finding an electron at that

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:19.270
radius, and that's the
definition we gave to the

00:07:19.270 --> 00:07:22.290
radial probability
distribution.

00:07:22.290 --> 00:07:25.370
And we can look at the formula
that got us here.

00:07:25.370 --> 00:07:29.210
This is the radial probability
distribution formula for an s

00:07:29.210 --> 00:07:32.150
orbital, which is, of course,
dealing with something that's

00:07:32.150 --> 00:07:33.650
spherically symmetrical.

00:07:33.650 --> 00:07:35.975
It's somewhat different when
we're talking about the p or

00:07:35.975 --> 00:07:38.170
the d orbitals, and we won't
go into the equation there,

00:07:38.170 --> 00:07:40.340
but this will give you an idea
of what we're really talking

00:07:40.340 --> 00:07:43.070
about with this radial
probability distribution.

00:07:43.070 --> 00:07:45.970
So, what we can do to actually
get a probability instead of a

00:07:45.970 --> 00:07:49.220
probability density that we're
talking about is to take the

00:07:49.220 --> 00:07:52.520
wave function squared, which
we know is probability

00:07:52.520 --> 00:07:57.380
density, and multiply it by the
volume of that very, very

00:07:57.380 --> 00:07:59.840
thin spherical shell that
we're talking about at

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:01.050
distance r.

00:08:01.050 --> 00:08:03.480
So if we want to talk about the
volume of that, we just

00:08:03.480 --> 00:08:07.850
talk about the surface area,
which is 4 pi r squared, and

00:08:07.850 --> 00:08:10.540
we multiply that by
the thickness d r.

00:08:10.540 --> 00:08:14.020
So if we take this term, which
is a volume term, and multiply

00:08:14.020 --> 00:08:17.310
it by probability over volume,
what we're going to end up

00:08:17.310 --> 00:08:21.060
with is an actual probability
of finding our electron at

00:08:21.060 --> 00:08:24.800
that distance, r, from
the nucleus.

00:08:24.800 --> 00:08:27.890
So, the example that we took
on Monday and that we ended

00:08:27.890 --> 00:08:31.760
with when we ended class, was
looking at the 1 s orbital for

00:08:31.760 --> 00:08:35.020
hydrogen atom, and what we could
do is we could graph the

00:08:35.020 --> 00:08:39.170
radial probability as a function
of radius here.

00:08:39.170 --> 00:08:42.890
And when we do that we can see
this curve, this probability

00:08:42.890 --> 00:08:46.940
curve, where we have a maximum
probability of finding the

00:08:46.940 --> 00:08:50.000
electron this far away
from the nucleus.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:54.120
And we call that most probable
radius r sub m p, or most

00:08:54.120 --> 00:08:55.420
probable radius.

00:08:55.420 --> 00:08:57.920
And what is discussed is that
for a 1 s hydrogen atom, that

00:08:57.920 --> 00:09:01.740
falls at an a nought distance
away from the nucleus.

00:09:01.740 --> 00:09:05.820
And remember, a nought, that's
just the Bohr radius, it's a

00:09:05.820 --> 00:09:07.650
constant -- that's all we
need to worry about.

00:09:07.650 --> 00:09:10.300
We talked about the Bohr
model and how that

00:09:10.300 --> 00:09:12.600
told us an exact distance.

00:09:12.600 --> 00:09:15.740
It was a classical model, right,
so we could say the

00:09:15.740 --> 00:09:18.290
electron is exactly this far
away from the nucleus.

00:09:18.290 --> 00:09:20.380
We can not do that with quantum
mechanics, the more

00:09:20.380 --> 00:09:23.590
true picture is the best we can
get to is talk about what

00:09:23.590 --> 00:09:26.270
the probability is of
finding the electron

00:09:26.270 --> 00:09:27.420
at any given nucleus.

00:09:27.420 --> 00:09:31.620
And the most probable one
here is that a nought.

00:09:31.620 --> 00:09:34.130
The other thing that we looked
at, which I want to stress

00:09:34.130 --> 00:09:36.780
again and I'll stress it as
many times as I can fit it

00:09:36.780 --> 00:09:39.960
into lecture, because this is
something that confuses

00:09:39.960 --> 00:09:42.170
students when they're trying
to identify, for example,

00:09:42.170 --> 00:09:44.910
different nodes or areas
of no probability.

00:09:44.910 --> 00:09:49.380
In an orbital is remember that
this area right here at r

00:09:49.380 --> 00:09:51.710
equals zerio, that
is not a node.

00:09:51.710 --> 00:09:54.750
We will always have r equals
zero in these radial

00:09:54.750 --> 00:09:57.950
probability distribution graphs,
and we can think about

00:09:57.950 --> 00:09:58.570
why that is.

00:09:58.570 --> 00:10:00.730
At first it might be
counter-intuitive because we

00:10:00.730 --> 00:10:03.850
know the probability density
at the nucleus is the

00:10:03.850 --> 00:10:07.010
greatest. So the probability of
having an electron at the

00:10:07.010 --> 00:10:09.490
nucleus in terms of probability
per volume is

00:10:09.490 --> 00:10:10.820
very, very high.

00:10:10.820 --> 00:10:13.480
But remember that we need to
multiply it by the volume

00:10:13.480 --> 00:10:16.350
here, the volume of some
sphere we've defined.

00:10:16.350 --> 00:10:19.220
And when we define that as
r being equal to zero,

00:10:19.220 --> 00:10:20.560
essentially we're
multiplying the

00:10:20.560 --> 00:10:22.700
probability density by zero.

00:10:22.700 --> 00:10:26.260
So that's why we have this zero
point here, and just to

00:10:26.260 --> 00:10:29.270
point out again and again and
again, it's not a radial node,

00:10:29.270 --> 00:10:32.280
it's just a point where we're
starting our graph, because

00:10:32.280 --> 00:10:36.980
we're multiplying it
by r equals zero.

00:10:36.980 --> 00:10:39.740
So, we can look at other
radial probability

00:10:39.740 --> 00:10:41.890
distributions of other
wave functions

00:10:41.890 --> 00:10:42.750
that we talked about.

00:10:42.750 --> 00:10:45.820
We talked about the wave
function for a 2 s orbital,

00:10:45.820 --> 00:10:48.470
and also for a 3 s orbital.

00:10:48.470 --> 00:10:55.270
So, let's go ahead and think
about drawing what that would

00:10:55.270 --> 00:10:57.610
look like in terms of the
radial probability

00:10:57.610 --> 00:10:59.390
distribution.

00:10:59.390 --> 00:11:03.650
So what we're graphing here is
the radius as a function of

00:11:03.650 --> 00:11:05.940
radial probability.

00:11:05.940 --> 00:11:11.280
And for a 2 s orbital, you get
a graph that's going to look

00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:14.090
something like this.

00:11:14.090 --> 00:11:16.200
So, again, we're starting
at zero.

00:11:16.200 --> 00:11:20.040
We have one node here, and we
can again define that most

00:11:20.040 --> 00:11:22.160
probable radius.

00:11:22.160 --> 00:11:26.050
And it turns out that for a 2
s orbital, that's equal to 6

00:11:26.050 --> 00:11:29.350
times a nought.

00:11:29.350 --> 00:11:31.600
So when we think about what
it is that this radial

00:11:31.600 --> 00:11:34.900
probability distribution is
telling us, it's telling us

00:11:34.900 --> 00:11:39.400
that it is most likely that an
electron in a 2 s orbital of

00:11:39.400 --> 00:11:43.960
hydrogen is six times further
away from the nucleus than it

00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:46.710
is in a 1 s orbital.

00:11:46.710 --> 00:11:50.110
So another way to say that is,
in a sense, if we're thinking

00:11:50.110 --> 00:11:52.620
about the excited state of a
hydrogen atom, the first

00:11:52.620 --> 00:11:57.510
excited state, or the n equals
2 state, what we're saying is

00:11:57.510 --> 00:12:01.430
that it's actually bigger than
the ground state, or the 1 s

00:12:01.430 --> 00:12:03.350
state of a hydrogen atom.

00:12:03.350 --> 00:12:05.770
And when we say bigger,
remember this is not a

00:12:05.770 --> 00:12:08.240
classical description
we're talking about.

00:12:08.240 --> 00:12:10.130
We are talking about
probability, but what we're

00:12:10.130 --> 00:12:13.710
saying is that most probable
radius is further away from

00:12:13.710 --> 00:12:16.280
the nucleus.

00:12:16.280 --> 00:12:20.020
So we can also look at this in
terms of the 3 s orbital.

00:12:20.020 --> 00:12:26.940
And in this case, we have
a graph that looks

00:12:26.940 --> 00:12:28.060
something like this.

00:12:28.060 --> 00:12:32.010
So you can draw that
into your notes.

00:12:32.010 --> 00:12:36.420
And again, we can define what
that most probable radius is,

00:12:36.420 --> 00:12:37.910
that distance at which
we're most

00:12:37.910 --> 00:12:40.840
likely to find an electron.

00:12:40.840 --> 00:12:43.280
And in the case of the 3 s
orbital, that's going to be

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:44.940
equal to 11 .

00:12:44.940 --> 00:12:48.540
5 times a nought.

00:12:48.540 --> 00:12:51.800
So again, what we're saying here
is that it is most likely

00:12:51.800 --> 00:12:55.580
in the 3 s orbital that we would
find the electron 11 and

00:12:55.580 --> 00:12:59.330
1/2 times further away from the
nucleus than we would in a

00:12:59.330 --> 00:13:03.110
around state hydrogen atom.

00:13:03.110 --> 00:13:05.470
And I just want to point out
here in terms of things that

00:13:05.470 --> 00:13:08.950
you're responsible for, you
should know that the most

00:13:08.950 --> 00:13:11.530
