00:19:33.590 --> 00:19:36.390
And so now we can move on to
thinking about p orbitals, we

00:19:36.390 --> 00:19:38.380
now have two ways to talk
about p orbitals.

00:19:38.380 --> 00:19:40.520
We can talk about the wave
function squared, the

00:19:40.520 --> 00:19:43.850
probability density, or we
can talk about the radial

00:19:43.850 --> 00:19:46.990
probability distribution.

00:19:46.990 --> 00:19:50.070
So when we talk about p
orbitals, it's similar to

00:19:50.070 --> 00:19:53.720
talking about s orbitals, and
the difference lies, and now

00:19:53.720 --> 00:19:57.470
we have a different value for
l, so l equals 1 for a p

00:19:57.470 --> 00:20:00.490
orbital, and we know if we have
l equal 1, we can have

00:20:00.490 --> 00:20:05.240
three different total orbitals
that have sub-shell of l

00:20:05.240 --> 00:20:06.650
equalling 1.

00:20:06.650 --> 00:20:11.300
So we can have, if we have the
final quantum number m equal

00:20:11.300 --> 00:20:13.710
plus 1 or minus 1, we're
dealing with a

00:20:13.710 --> 00:20:16.420
p x or a p y orbital.

00:20:16.420 --> 00:20:18.650
Remember, we don't do a
one-to-one correlation,

00:20:18.650 --> 00:20:22.930
because p x and p y are some
linear combination of the m

00:20:22.930 --> 00:20:25.550
plus 1 and m minus 1 orbital.

00:20:25.550 --> 00:20:28.040
And if we talk about
m equals 0, we're

00:20:28.040 --> 00:20:29.650
looking at the p z orbital.

00:20:29.650 --> 00:20:36.810
And the significant difference
between s orbitals and p

00:20:36.810 --> 00:20:40.190
orbitals that comes from the
fact that we do have angular

00:20:40.190 --> 00:20:43.350
momentum here in these p
orbitals, is that p orbital

00:20:43.350 --> 00:20:47.130
wave functions do, in fact, have
theta and phi dependence.

00:20:47.130 --> 00:20:49.320
So they do have an angular
dependence that

00:20:49.320 --> 00:20:52.280
we're talking about.

00:20:52.280 --> 00:20:54.430
And what I'm showing here is not
on your notes, if you're

00:20:54.430 --> 00:20:56.420
interested you can look
it up in your book.

00:20:56.420 --> 00:20:58.870
This is a table that's directly
from your book, and

00:20:58.870 --> 00:21:01.580
what it's just showing is the
wave function for a bunch of

00:21:01.580 --> 00:21:02.030
different orbitals.

00:21:02.030 --> 00:21:04.480
I mentioned last time
that there was this

00:21:04.480 --> 00:21:05.840
list in your book.

00:21:05.840 --> 00:21:09.170
And what I want to point out
here is this angular

00:21:09.170 --> 00:21:13.020
dependence for the p orbitals
for the l equals 1 orbital.

00:21:13.020 --> 00:21:17.880
So, first, if I point out when
l equals 0, when we have an s

00:21:17.880 --> 00:21:21.410
orbital, what you see is that
angular part of the wave

00:21:21.410 --> 00:21:23.600
function is equal
to a constant.

00:21:23.600 --> 00:21:26.250
So, remember we can break up the
total wave function into

00:21:26.250 --> 00:21:30.470
the radial part and
the angular part.

00:21:30.470 --> 00:21:31.860
When we look at this angular
part, we see that it's always

00:21:31.860 --> 00:21:35.280
the square root of 1 over 4 pi,
it doesn't matter what the

00:21:35.280 --> 00:21:39.550
angle is, it's not dependent
on the angle.

00:21:39.550 --> 00:21:43.410
In contrast when we're looking
at a p orbital, so any time l

00:21:43.410 --> 00:21:46.960
is equal to 1, and you look at
angular part of the wave

00:21:46.960 --> 00:21:49.750
function here, what you see is
the wave function either

00:21:49.750 --> 00:21:52.450
depends on theta or
is dependent on

00:21:52.450 --> 00:21:54.370
both theta and phi.

00:21:54.370 --> 00:21:57.210
So we do, in fact, have a
dependence on what the angle

00:21:57.210 --> 00:22:01.890
is of the electron as we define
it in the orbital.

00:22:01.890 --> 00:22:06.480
So what this means is that
unlike s orbitals, p orbitals

00:22:06.480 --> 00:22:09.690
are not spherically symmetrical
-- they don't have

00:22:09.690 --> 00:22:13.770
the exact same shape at any
radius from the nucleus.

00:22:13.770 --> 00:22:18.330
And these shapes of p orbitals
probably do look familiar to

00:22:18.330 --> 00:22:20.680
you, most of you, I'm sure, have
seen some sort of picture

00:22:20.680 --> 00:22:22.670
of p orbitals before.

00:22:22.670 --> 00:22:25.270
So what I want to point out
about them is that they're

00:22:25.270 --> 00:22:28.790
made up of two nodes, and what
you can see is that nodes are

00:22:28.790 --> 00:22:30.650
shown in different colors
here and those

00:22:30.650 --> 00:22:32.220
are different phases.

00:22:32.220 --> 00:22:35.750
Sometimes you see this written
when you see p orbitals, one

00:22:35.750 --> 00:22:38.210
is written as plus, one
is written in minus.

00:22:38.210 --> 00:22:40.430
That's not a positive and
negative charge, that's

00:22:40.430 --> 00:22:43.760
actually a phase, and that
arises from the wave equation.

00:22:43.760 --> 00:22:46.190
Remember when we have waves
we can have positive or a

00:22:46.190 --> 00:22:46.910
negative amplitude.

00:22:46.910 --> 00:22:50.690
When we talk about p orbitals
the phase of the orbital

00:22:50.690 --> 00:22:54.170
becomes important once we talk
about bonding, which hopefully

00:22:54.170 --> 00:22:55.920
you were happy to hear at
the beginning of class

00:22:55.920 --> 00:22:57.200
we will get to soon.

00:22:57.200 --> 00:23:00.410
And it turns out that when you
constructively have two p

00:23:00.410 --> 00:23:03.700
orbitals interfere, and when I
say constructively, I mean

00:23:03.700 --> 00:23:06.140
they're both either positive or
they're both the negative

00:23:06.140 --> 00:23:08.250
lobes, that's when
you got bonding.

00:23:08.250 --> 00:23:12.170
Whereas if the phases where
mismatched, you

00:23:12.170 --> 00:23:13.760
would not get bonding.

00:23:13.760 --> 00:23:16.380
So, that's going to be important
later when we get to

00:23:16.380 --> 00:23:18.980
bonding, but just take note of
it now, we have two nodes,

00:23:18.980 --> 00:23:24.490
each with a separate phase --
or we have two lobes, excuse

00:23:24.490 --> 00:23:26.020
me, each with a separate
phase.

00:23:26.020 --> 00:23:28.760
And when we look at this, it's
actually split by what's

00:23:28.760 --> 00:23:31.980
called a nodal plane, which is
pointed out in light orange

00:23:31.980 --> 00:23:34.910
here on this picture, but what
we just mean is that there is

00:23:34.910 --> 00:23:37.970
this whole plane that separates
the two lobes where

00:23:37.970 --> 00:23:41.250
there is absolutely no
electron density.

00:23:41.250 --> 00:23:43.790
So, the wave function at all of
these points in this plane

00:23:43.790 --> 00:23:45.980
is equal to zero, so therefore,
also the wave

00:23:45.980 --> 00:23:50.930
function squared is going
to be equal to zero.

00:23:50.930 --> 00:23:56.020
So, if we say that in this
entire plane we have zero

00:23:56.020 --> 00:23:58.810
probability of finding a p
electron anywhere in the

00:23:58.810 --> 00:24:02.420
plane, the plane goes directly
through the nucleus in every

00:24:02.420 --> 00:24:05.660
case but a p orbital, so what we
can also say is that there

00:24:05.660 --> 00:24:13.850
is zero probability of finding
a p electron at the nucleus.

00:24:13.850 --> 00:24:17.320
So, again we can use these
probability density plots,

00:24:17.320 --> 00:24:23.160
which are just a plot of psi
squared, where the density of

00:24:23.160 --> 00:24:26.630
the dots is proportional to the
density, the probability

00:24:26.630 --> 00:24:28.730
density, at that point.

00:24:28.730 --> 00:24:31.850
So what we can say is look at
each of these separately, so

00:24:31.850 --> 00:24:36.430
if we start with looking at the
2 p z orbital, the highest

00:24:36.430 --> 00:24:40.000
probability of finding an
electron in the 2 p z orbital,

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:42.180
is going to be along
this z-axis.

00:24:42.180 --> 00:24:44.770
We can see that right here.

00:24:44.770 --> 00:24:48.630
And in terms of thinking about
the phase of this p orbital,

00:24:48.630 --> 00:24:50.520
the phase is going
to be positive

00:24:50.520 --> 00:24:52.250
anywhere where z is positive.

00:24:52.250 --> 00:24:55.780
So we would say we have a
positive phase here and a

00:24:55.780 --> 00:24:57.140
negative phase there.

00:24:57.140 --> 00:24:59.200
Remember, that's going to become
important when we talk

00:24:59.200 --> 00:25:01.030
about bonding, we don't
need to worry about it

00:25:01.030 --> 00:25:03.280
too much right now.

00:25:03.280 --> 00:25:07.420
We can also think about where
the nodal plane is in this p z

00:25:07.420 --> 00:25:11.060
orbital, so how would we define
the nodal plane here?

00:25:11.060 --> 00:25:16.580
What would the nodal plane be?

00:25:16.580 --> 00:25:18.950
So, it's the x-y plane, you can
see there's no electron

00:25:18.950 --> 00:25:20.940
density anywhere there.

00:25:20.940 --> 00:25:23.760
And similarly, actually, if
we're looking at our polar

00:25:23.760 --> 00:25:27.540
coordinates here, what we see is
it's any place where theta

00:25:27.540 --> 00:25:31.080
is equal to 0 is what's going
to put up on the x-y plane.

00:25:31.080 --> 00:25:33.900
So another way to define the
nodal plane is where theta is

00:25:33.900 --> 00:25:36.820
equal to 90 degrees.

00:25:36.820 --> 00:25:40.450
So let's look now at
the 2 p x orbital.

00:25:40.450 --> 00:25:43.140
This is the probability density
map, so we're talking

00:25:43.140 --> 00:25:44.680
about the square here.

00:25:44.680 --> 00:25:48.320
The highest probability now is
going to be along the x-axis,

00:25:48.320 --> 00:25:52.060
so that means we're going to
have a positive wave function

00:25:52.060 --> 00:25:54.420
every place where
x is positive.

00:25:54.420 --> 00:25:56.290
What is the nodal plane
in this case?

00:25:56.290 --> 00:25:57.990
Um-hmm.

00:25:57.990 --> 00:26:02.030
So, it's going to be the y z
nodal plane, or in other

00:26:02.030 --> 00:26:04.460
words, we can say it's
any place where phi

00:26:04.460 --> 00:26:06.360
is equal to 90 degrees.

00:26:06.360 --> 00:26:09.190
So you can see if you take phi,
and you move it over 90

00:26:09.190 --> 00:26:11.580
degrees, we're right here
in the y z plane.

00:26:11.580 --> 00:26:13.820
Anywhere where that's the case
we're going to have no

00:26:13.820 --> 00:26:17.530
probability density of
finding an electron.

00:26:17.530 --> 00:26:20.910
And finally, we can look at
the 2 p y, so the highest

00:26:20.910 --> 00:26:23.590
probability is going to
be along the y-axis.

00:26:23.590 --> 00:26:26.360
It's going to be positive in
terms of its wave function or

00:26:26.360 --> 00:26:29.590
in terms of its phase anywhere
where y is positive.

00:26:29.590 --> 00:26:33.520
And the nodal plane's going to
be in the x z plane, or again,

00:26:33.520 --> 00:26:37.430
anywhere where phi is going to
be equal to 0, that takes us

00:26:37.430 --> 00:26:41.440
to the x z plane.

00:26:41.440 --> 00:26:44.550
So, let me get a little bit more
specific about what we

00:26:44.550 --> 00:26:47.590
mean by nodal plane and where
the idea of nodal plane comes

00:26:47.590 --> 00:26:51.000
from, and nodal planes arise
from any place you have

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:52.830
angular nodes.

00:26:52.830 --> 00:26:55.430
So we talked about radial nodes
when we're doing these

00:26:55.430 --> 00:26:58.350
radial probability density
diagrams here.

00:26:58.350 --> 00:27:00.930
You can also have angular notes,
and when we talk about

00:27:00.930 --> 00:27:04.460
an anglar node, what we're
talking about is values of

00:27:04.460 --> 00:27:07.570
theta or values of phi at which
the wave function, and

00:27:07.570 --> 00:27:10.270
therefore, the wave function
squared, or the probability

00:27:10.270 --> 00:27:13.400
density are going to
be equal to zero.

00:27:13.400 --> 00:27:17.570
So, you remember from last time
radial nodes are values

00:27:17.570 --> 00:27:21.040
of r at which the wave function
and wave function

00:27:21.040 --> 00:27:23.680
squared are zero, so the
difference is now we're just

00:27:23.680 --> 00:27:26.910
talking about the angular part
of the wave function.

00:27:26.910 --> 00:27:29.440
And, in fact, these are the only
two types of nodes that

00:27:29.440 --> 00:27:32.600
we're going to be describing,
so we can actually calculate

00:27:32.600 --> 00:27:35.490
both the total number of notes
and the number of each type of

00:27:35.490 --> 00:27:39.170
node we should expect to see
in any type of orbital.

00:27:39.170 --> 00:27:41.980
And our equation for total nodes
is just the principle

00:27:41.980 --> 00:27:43.810
quantum number minus 1.

00:27:43.810 --> 00:27:46.690
And when we talk about angular
nodes, the number of angular

00:27:46.690 --> 00:27:50.820
nodes we have in an orbital
is going to be equal to l.

00:27:50.820 --> 00:27:54.490
So that's why we saw, for
example, in the p orbitals we

00:27:54.490 --> 00:27:57.470
had one angular node in each
p orbital, because l

00:27:57.470 --> 00:27:58.880
is equal to 1 there.

00:27:58.880 --> 00:28:01.650
And we talked about the equation
you can use for

00:28:01.650 --> 00:28:07.520
radial nodes last time, and
that's just n minus 1 minus l.

00:28:07.520 --> 00:28:10.460
You can go ahead and use that
equation, or you could figure

00:28:10.460 --> 00:28:12.690
it out every time, because if
you know the total number of

00:28:12.690 --> 00:28:15.450
nodes, and you know the angular
node number, then you

00:28:15.450 --> 00:28:17.160
know how many nodes you're
going to have left.

00:28:17.160 --> 00:28:18.710
So you don't really have
to memorize that.

00:28:18.710 --> 00:28:22.760
So, let's go ahead and just
do a few of these.

00:28:22.760 --> 00:28:24.990
They're pretty straight forward
to do and it gives us

00:28:24.990 --> 00:28:27.430
an idea what kind of nodal
structure we can

00:28:27.430 --> 00:28:28.990
expect it an orbital.

00:28:28.990 --> 00:28:34.050
So for a 2 s orbital, how many
total nodes will we have?

00:28:34.050 --> 00:28:38.700
Yup, I heard one, so 2 minus
1, one total node.

00:28:38.700 --> 00:28:41.190
Angular nodes, we're not going
to have any of those, we'll

00:28:41.190 --> 00:28:45.820
have zero, l equals 0, so we
have zero angular nodes.

00:28:45.820 --> 00:28:51.240
And in terms of radial nodes, we
have 2 minus 1 minus 0, so

00:28:51.240 --> 00:28:54.130
what we have is one
radial node.

00:28:54.130 --> 00:28:56.720
So, what you find with the s
orbital, and this is general

00:28:56.720 --> 00:29:00.610
for all s orbitals is that all
of your nodes end up being

00:29:00.610 --> 00:29:01.370
radial nodes.

00:29:01.370 --> 00:29:02.990
That has to be the
case because l

00:29:02.990 --> 00:29:06.490
equals 0 for s orbitals.

00:29:06.490 --> 00:29:08.990
Let's look now at a p orbital,
so how many total

00:29:08.990 --> 00:29:13.720
nodes do we have here?

00:29:13.720 --> 00:29:18.630
Yup, so one total node, 2 minus
1 is 1, and that means

00:29:18.630 --> 00:29:23.160
since l is equal to 1, we have
one angular nodes, and that

00:29:23.160 --> 00:29:26.710
leaves us with how many
radial nodes?

00:29:26.710 --> 00:29:28.620
Yup, zero radial nodes.

00:29:28.620 --> 00:29:32.440
So, for a 2 p orbital, all the
nodes actually turn out to be

00:29:32.440 --> 00:29:35.070
angular nodes.

00:29:35.070 --> 00:29:37.900
So, let's have you try one more,
if we can switch over

00:29:37.900 --> 00:29:41.270
and talk about a 3 d orbital.

00:29:41.270 --> 00:29:44.000
So, I'm asking very specifically
about radial

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:47.090
nodes here, how many radial
nodes does a hydrogen atom 3 d

00:29:47.090 --> 00:29:48.200
orbital have?

00:29:48.200 --> 00:29:56.470
So, you can go ahead and take
10 seconds on that.

00:29:56.470 --> 00:30:09.530
All right.

00:30:09.530 --> 00:30:12.550
So most of you got that, though
there is this little

00:30:12.550 --> 00:30:16.090
sub-set we have thinking that we
have one, so let's actually

00:30:16.090 --> 00:30:17.950
write this out here.

00:30:17.950 --> 00:30:24.450
So if we have a 3 d orbital,
we're talking about n minus l

00:30:24.450 --> 00:30:28.180
minus 1, what is n equal to?

00:30:28.180 --> 00:30:30.180
What is l equal to?

00:30:30.180 --> 00:30:33.560
OK. and 1 is equal to 1.

00:30:33.560 --> 00:30:37.010
So, it turns out that we have
zero nodes that we're dealing

00:30:37.010 --> 00:30:39.070
with when we're talking
about a 3 d orbital.

00:30:39.070 --> 00:30:43.860
OK.

00:30:43.860 --> 00:30:46.400
So we should be able to figure
this out for any orbital that

00:30:46.400 --> 00:30:50.490
we're discussing, and when we
can figure out especially

00:30:50.490 --> 00:30:53.580
radial nodes, we have a good
head start on going ahead and

00:30:53.580 --> 00:30:57.070
thinking about drawing radial
probability distributions.

00:30:57.070 --> 00:30:59.700
We did it for the s orbitals,
we can also do it for the p,

00:30:59.700 --> 00:31:00.850
we can do it for the d.

00:31:00.850 --> 00:31:03.200
All we have to figure out is how
many nodes we're dealing

00:31:03.200 --> 00:31:05.170
with and then we can get
the general shape

00:31:05.170 --> 00:31:07.170
of the graph here.

00:31:07.170 --> 00:31:10.620
So, let's actually compare
the radial probability

00:31:10.620 --> 00:31:13.910
distribution of p orbitals to
what we've already looked at,

00:31:13.910 --> 00:31:16.580
which are s orbitals, and we'll
find that we can get

00:31:16.580 --> 00:31:20.410
some information out of
comparing these graphs.

00:31:20.410 --> 00:31:23.860
So if we draw the 2 p orbital,
what we just figured out was

00:31:23.860 --> 00:31:25.870
there should be zero
radial nodes, so

00:31:25.870 --> 00:31:27.950
that's what we see here.

00:31:27.950 --> 00:31:30.200
The other thing that I want you
to notice, is if you look

00:31:30.200 --> 00:31:34.010
at the most probable radius,
for the 2 s orbital it's

00:31:34.010 --> 00:31:37.560
actually out further away from
the nucleus than it is for the

00:31:37.560 --> 00:31:39.320
2 p orbital.

00:31:39.320 --> 00:31:43.420
So what we can say here is that
the 2 p is less than or

00:31:43.420 --> 00:31:46.930
smaller than the 2 s orbital.

00:31:46.930 --> 00:31:49.590
So think about what that means,
we're, of course, not

00:31:49.590 --> 00:31:51.580
talking about this in classical
terms, so what it

00:31:51.580 --> 00:31:55.390
means if we have an electron in
the 2 p orbital, it's more

00:31:55.390 --> 00:31:58.190
likely, the probability is that
will be closer to the

00:31:58.190 --> 00:32:03.080
nucleus than it would be if it
were in the 2 s orbital.

00:32:03.080 --> 00:32:06.720
We can also take a look the 3
s, which we have looked at

00:32:06.720 --> 00:32:09.440
before, and we figured out
that that should have two

00:32:09.440 --> 00:32:10.880
radial nodes.

00:32:10.880 --> 00:32:14.850
We can look at the 2 p, which
should have one radial node,

00:32:14.850 --> 00:32:18.980
and we just figured it out for
the, excuse me, for the 3 p

00:32:18.980 --> 00:32:22.840
has one radial node, and for the
3 d here, we should have

00:32:22.840 --> 00:32:25.370
zero radial nodes, we just
calculated that.

00:32:25.370 --> 00:32:28.570
So again, what we see is the
same pattern where the most

00:32:28.570 --> 00:32:32.070
probable radius, if we talk
about it in terms of the d,

00:32:32.070 --> 00:32:35.270
that's going to be smaller then
for the p, and the 3 p

00:32:35.270 --> 00:32:38.330
most probable radius is going
to be closer to the nucleus

00:32:38.330 --> 00:32:43.200
than it is for the 3 s most
probable radius that we're

00:32:43.200 --> 00:32:45.160
looking at.

00:32:45.160 --> 00:32:47.960
So, there are 2 different things
that we can compare

00:32:47.960 --> 00:32:50.950
when we're comparing graphs
of radial probability

00:32:50.950 --> 00:32:54.660
distribution, and the first
thing we can do is think about

00:32:54.660 --> 00:32:57.500
well, how does the radius
change, or the most probable

00:32:57.500 --> 00:33:00.540
radius change when we're
increasing n, when we're

00:33:00.540 --> 00:33:03.860
increasing the principle
quantum number here?

00:33:03.860 --> 00:33:07.290
So, from going from the shell
of n equals 2, let's say, to

00:33:07.290 --> 00:33:09.090
the shell of n equals 3.

00:33:09.090 --> 00:33:13.500
And what we find is we're going
from about or exactly a

00:33:13.500 --> 00:33:17.410
6 a nought here, to almost three
times that when we're

00:33:17.410 --> 00:33:19.650
going from 2 s to 3 s.

00:33:19.650 --> 00:33:22.940
So we say if n increases,
the orbital size is

00:33:22.940 --> 00:33:23.990
also going to increase.

00:33:23.990 --> 00:33:26.140
And when we talk about size,
I'm again just going to say

00:33:26.140 --> 00:33:29.260
the stipulation that we're
talking about, probability --

00:33:29.260 --> 00:33:32.420
we're not talking about an
absolute classical concept

00:33:32.420 --> 00:33:36.210
here, but in general we're going
to picture it being much

00:33:36.210 --> 00:33:40.920
further away from the nucleus
as we move up in terms of n.

00:33:40.920 --> 00:33:44.210
The other thing that we took
note as is what happens as l

00:33:44.210 --> 00:33:47.890
increases, and specifically as
l increases for any given the

00:33:47.890 --> 00:33:49.280
principle quantum number.

00:33:49.280 --> 00:33:52.890
So if we're keeping n the same,
we look and what we saw

00:33:52.890 --> 00:33:56.340
was that size actually decreases
as we increase the

00:33:56.340 --> 00:33:58.610
value of l.

00:33:58.610 --> 00:34:02.230
So, I want to contrast that
with another concept that

00:34:02.230 --> 00:34:06.330
seemed to be opposing ideas, and
that is thinking about not

00:34:06.330 --> 00:34:10.000
how far away the most probable
radius is, but thinking about

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:13.546
how close an electron can get
to the nucleus if it's

00:34:13.546 --> 00:34:14.380
actually in that orbital.

00:34:14.380 --> 00:34:18.370
And what we'll find is that we
actually see the opposite.

00:34:18.370 --> 00:34:24.150
So if we compare l increasing
here, so a 3 s to a 3 p to a 3

00:34:24.150 --> 00:34:28.550
d, what we find is that it's
only in the s orbital that we

00:34:28.550 --> 00:34:31.920
have a significant probability
of actually getting very close

00:34:31.920 --> 00:34:33.140
to the nucleus.

00:34:33.140 --> 00:34:37.130
So, if I kind of circle where
the probability gets somewhat

00:34:37.130 --> 00:34:39.910
substantial here, you can see
we're much closer to the

00:34:39.910 --> 00:34:44.390
nucleus at the s orbital than we
are for the p, then when we

00:34:44.390 --> 00:34:46.350
are for the d.

00:34:46.350 --> 00:34:51.150
So, the size still for an s
orbital is larger than for a d

00:34:51.150 --> 00:34:54.330
orbital, but what we say is
that an s electron can

00:34:54.330 --> 00:34:56.950
actually penetrate closer
to the nucleus.

00:34:56.950 --> 00:34:59.940
There's some probability that
it can get very, very close

00:34:59.940 --> 00:35:01.850
the nucleus, and that
probability is actually

00:35:01.850 --> 00:35:05.470
substantial.

00:35:05.470 --> 00:35:11.140
A kind of consequence of this
is if we're thinking about a

00:35:11.140 --> 00:35:13.880
multi-electron atom, which we'll
get to in a minute where

00:35:13.880 --> 00:35:16.810
electrons can shield each other
from the pull of the

00:35:16.810 --> 00:35:19.780
nucleus, we're going to say that
the electrons in the s

00:35:19.780 --> 00:35:22.110
orbitals are actually
the least shielded.

00:35:22.110 --> 00:35:24.520
And the reason that they're the
least sheilded is because

00:35:24.520 --> 00:35:26.650
they can get closest to the
nucleus, so we can think of

00:35:26.650 --> 00:35:29.430
them as not getting blocked by
a bunch of other electron,

00:35:29.430 --> 00:35:31.010
because there's some probability
that they can

00:35:31.010 --> 00:35:33.970
actually work their way all
the way in to the nucleus.

00:35:33.970 --> 00:35:35.450
So, this is a concept
that's going to

00:35:35.450 --> 00:35:36.990
become really important.

00:35:36.990 --> 00:35:39.520
Soon when we're talking about
multi-electron atoms, and I

00:35:39.520 --> 00:35:41.870
just want to introduce it
here, that it is sort of

00:35:41.870 --> 00:35:45.090
opposing ideas that even though
the s is the biggest

00:35:45.090 --> 00:35:47.440
and it's most likely that the
electron's going to be

00:35:47.440 --> 00:35:50.280
furthest away from the nucleus,
that's also the

00:35:50.280 --> 00:35:54.500
orbital in which the electron
can, in fact, penetrate

00:35:54.500 --> 00:35:56.370
closest.

00:35:56.370 --> 00:35:56.690
All right.

00:35:56.690 --> 00:35:59.390
So I think we are, in fact,
ready to move on to

00:35:59.390 --> 00:36:04.190
multi-electron atoms, and what
happens is when we solved the

00:36:04.190 --> 00:36:07.550
relativistic version of the
Schrodinger equation and we're

00:36:07.550 --> 00:36:10.790
discussing more than one
electron, we actually have a

00:36:10.790 --> 00:36:13.880
fourth quantum number that falls
out and that we need to

00:36:13.880 --> 00:36:16.000
deal with and this is
called the electron

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:17.530
spin quantum number.

00:36:17.530 --> 00:36:20.330
And I promise, this is the last
quantum number that we'll

00:36:20.330 --> 00:36:22.750
be introducing.

00:36:22.750 --> 00:36:26.490
And this spin magnetic quantum
number we abbreviate as m sub

00:36:26.490 --> 00:36:32.580
s, so that's to differentiate
from m sub l.

00:36:32.580 --> 00:36:36.320
And when you solved the
relativistic form of the

00:36:36.320 --> 00:36:38.730
Schrodinger equation, what you
end up with is that you can

00:36:38.730 --> 00:36:41.580
have two possible values
for the magnetic

00:36:41.580 --> 00:36:43.580
spin quantum number.

00:36:43.580 --> 00:36:47.940
You can have it equal to plus
1/2, and that's what we call

00:36:47.940 --> 00:36:51.730
spin up, or you can have it
equal to minus 1/2, which is

00:36:51.730 --> 00:36:53.760
what we call spin down.

00:36:53.760 --> 00:36:56.970
So, there's two kind of cartoons
shown here that give

00:36:56.970 --> 00:36:59.420
you a little bit of an idea
of what this quantum

00:36:59.420 --> 00:37:00.660
number tells us.

00:37:00.660 --> 00:37:04.870
And this spin is an intrinsic
quality of the electron, it's

00:37:04.870 --> 00:37:08.080
a property that is intrinsic in
all particles, just like we

00:37:08.080 --> 00:37:10.970
would say mass is intrinsic
or charge is intrinsic.

00:37:10.970 --> 00:37:13.750
Spin is also an intrinsic
property.

00:37:13.750 --> 00:37:16.140
One way to think about it, if
we want to use a classical

00:37:16.140 --> 00:37:18.610
analogy, which often helps to
give us an idea of what's

00:37:18.610 --> 00:37:21.760
going on, is the spin of an
electron, we can picture it

00:37:21.760 --> 00:37:24.010
rotating on its own axis.

00:37:24.010 --> 00:37:27.350
So that's kind of what's shown
in these pictures here.

00:37:27.350 --> 00:37:29.350
So you can see, if it's spinning
on its own axis in

00:37:29.350 --> 00:37:31.960
this direction we'd call it spin
up, where as this way it

00:37:31.960 --> 00:37:34.010
would be what we
call spin down.

00:37:34.010 --> 00:37:36.910
So, it turns out there's not
actually a good classical

00:37:36.910 --> 00:37:40.140
analogy for spin, we can't
really think of it like that,

00:37:40.140 --> 00:37:43.300
but if that helps give you an
idea of what's going on here

00:37:43.300 --> 00:37:45.750
then it's valuable maybe to
consider it spinning on its

00:37:45.750 --> 00:37:48.960
own axis, even though that's not
technically what's exactly

00:37:48.960 --> 00:37:49.980
happening here.

00:37:49.980 --> 00:37:52.570
But the reason that I like that
analogy is that it points

00:37:52.570 --> 00:37:56.130
out a very important part of
spin, and that's the idea that

00:37:56.130 --> 00:37:58.570
it's a description
of the electron.

00:37:58.570 --> 00:38:01.490
It is not dependent on
the actual orbital.

00:38:01.490 --> 00:38:04.830
So we can completely describe
an orbital with just using

00:38:04.830 --> 00:38:08.100
three quantum numbers, but we
have this fourth quantum

00:38:08.100 --> 00:38:10.760
number that describes something
about the electron

00:38:10.760 --> 00:38:13.840
that's required for now a
complete description of the

00:38:13.840 --> 00:38:16.550
electron, and that's
the idea of spin.

00:38:16.550 --> 00:38:19.490
So, we need to actually add on
this fourth quantum number,

00:38:19.490 --> 00:38:25.000
and it's either going to be
plus 1/2 or negative 1/2.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:27.230
So, we can talk a little bit
actually, because it's an

00:38:27.230 --> 00:38:30.650
interesting story about where
the idea of spin came from,

00:38:30.650 --> 00:38:33.590
and it was actually first
proposed by two very young

00:38:33.590 --> 00:38:37.310
scientists at the time, George
Uhlenbeck shown here, and

00:38:37.310 --> 00:38:40.370
Samuel Goudsmit who's here, and
they're with a friend, and

00:38:40.370 --> 00:38:43.680
I can't remember who that is,
but he did not have anything

00:38:43.680 --> 00:38:46.210
to do with discovering spin.

00:38:46.210 --> 00:38:48.310
And what you can see in this
picture is that these are

00:38:48.310 --> 00:38:50.060
actually, they're pretty young
guys in this picture.

00:38:50.060 --> 00:38:51.910
I think this is taken about
two years after they

00:38:51.910 --> 00:38:53.930
discovered the fourth
quantum number.

00:38:53.930 --> 00:38:56.500
So hopefully, you can picture
yourself at this age in a

00:38:56.500 --> 00:39:00.010
similar situation with an
anonymous friend and think

00:39:00.010 --> 00:39:02.780
this is something, kind of
observations maybe you can

00:39:02.780 --> 00:39:04.820
make as well.

00:39:04.820 --> 00:39:07.320
And what they were doing when
they discovered that there

00:39:07.320 --> 00:39:10.100
must be this fourth quantum
number is they were looking at

00:39:10.100 --> 00:39:14.730
the emission spectrum of sodium,
and, so specifically,

00:39:14.730 --> 00:39:17.630
they were looking at the
frequencies, and if we think

00:39:17.630 --> 00:39:20.600
about the frequencies of sodium,
it was already known

00:39:20.600 --> 00:39:22.930
at this time that you could
calculate what those would be

00:39:22.930 --> 00:39:25.110
based on the difference in the
energy levels -- this happened

00:39:25.110 --> 00:39:27.060
in about 1925.

00:39:27.060 --> 00:39:29.570
So they actually knew exactly
what they were expecting.

00:39:29.570 --> 00:39:31.930
So, let's say they were
expecting to see one certain

00:39:31.930 --> 00:39:36.150
frequency or one line in the
spectrum at this point here.

00:39:36.150 --> 00:39:40.740
It turns out that what they
actually observed, so this is

00:39:40.740 --> 00:39:44.830
the actual of what they saw,
is if they were expecting

00:39:44.830 --> 00:39:47.890
their line at some given
frequency, which I'll show by

00:39:47.890 --> 00:39:52.720
this dotted line here, what
they actually saw was two

00:39:52.720 --> 00:39:56.570
lines, and one was just the
teeniest tiniest bit of a

00:39:56.570 --> 00:39:59.690
higher frequency than what was
expected, and one was just,

00:39:59.690 --> 00:40:01.660
just below what they expected.

00:40:01.660 --> 00:40:04.460
And if we're talking about
things in spectroscopy terms

00:40:04.460 --> 00:40:08.840
here, this is what we
call a doublet.

00:40:08.840 --> 00:40:11.190
So it's centered at this
frequency that was expected,

00:40:11.190 --> 00:40:14.350
but it's actually split into
two different frequencies.

00:40:14.350 --> 00:40:16.930
And this was an amazing
observation that they made.

00:40:16.930 --> 00:40:19.620
They were totally surprised
and excited, and they were

00:40:19.620 --> 00:40:22.100
thinking how could this happen,
where did we got this

00:40:22.100 --> 00:40:23.650
split doublet from.

00:40:23.650 --> 00:40:26.600
And what they could come up
with, what they reasoned, is

00:40:26.600 --> 00:40:29.130
that there must be some
intrinsic property within the

00:40:29.130 --> 00:40:32.270
electron, because we know that
this describes the complete

00:40:32.270 --> 00:40:37.780
energy of the orbital should
give us one single frequency.

00:40:37.780 --> 00:40:40.810
And that the fact that it split
into two was telling

00:40:40.810 --> 00:40:43.970
them that there must be some new
property to the electron,

00:40:43.970 --> 00:40:45.930
and what we call that
now is either being

00:40:45.930 --> 00:40:47.880
spin up or spin down.

00:40:47.880 --> 00:40:51.420
But at the time, they didn't
have a well-formed name for

00:40:51.420 --> 00:40:54.210
it, they were just saying OK,
there's this fourth quantum

00:40:54.210 --> 00:40:57.480
number, there's this intrinsic
property in the electron.

00:40:57.480 --> 00:40:59.910
So, where the story gets kind
of unfortunate, but also a

00:40:59.910 --> 00:41:03.000
little bit more interesting is
the fact that well, they did

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:06.030
publish what they observed, and
they did write that up.

00:41:06.030 --> 00:41:08.220
They put it in a pretty
low impact paper.

00:41:08.220 --> 00:41:11.740
I think it was in French, so it
wasn't really hitting all

00:41:11.740 --> 00:41:15.930
the scientific community of
the time in any major way.

00:41:15.930 --> 00:41:19.310
And they didn't put their
explanation of what they

00:41:19.310 --> 00:41:21.500
thought was going on,
it just sort of was

00:41:21.500 --> 00:41:23.860
observing what they saw.

00:41:23.860 --> 00:41:26.210
These were very young
scientists, of course, so what

00:41:26.210 --> 00:41:28.650
you would expect that they would
do, which makes sense,

00:41:28.650 --> 00:41:30.850
is go to someone more
established in their field,

00:41:30.850 --> 00:41:33.100
because they have the
completely radical

00:41:33.100 --> 00:41:36.760
revolutionary idea, let's just
run it by someone before we go

00:41:36.760 --> 00:41:39.540
ahead and publish this paper
that makes this huge statement

00:41:39.540 --> 00:41:41.560
about this fourth
quantum number.

00:41:41.560 --> 00:41:44.520
So the person they chose to talk
to, and I think it was

00:41:44.520 --> 00:41:47.290
just Goudsmit that went to him
and discussed it is Wolfgang

00:41:47.290 --> 00:41:49.480
Pauli, which is shown here.

00:41:49.480 --> 00:41:52.030
So how many before five
minutes ago had

00:41:52.030 --> 00:41:52.840
heard the name Goudsmit?

00:41:52.840 --> 00:41:55.620
All right, a couple.

00:41:55.620 --> 00:41:56.850
OK, cool.

00:41:56.850 --> 00:41:59.580
How about Pauli, like the Pauli
exclusion principle?

00:41:59.580 --> 00:42:00.750
Hmm, OK.

00:42:00.750 --> 00:42:05.480
So, Pauli seems to be getting
a little bit of fame that

00:42:05.480 --> 00:42:06.710
you'll see in a second here.

00:42:06.710 --> 00:42:09.870
So, it turns out they go and
they discuss their idea with

00:42:09.870 --> 00:42:14.580
Pauli, and what Pauli tells
them is that this idea is

00:42:14.580 --> 00:42:17.120
ridiculous, that it's rubbish,
if they go ahead and try to

00:42:17.120 --> 00:42:19.150
publish this their scientific
careers are ruined.

00:42:19.150 --> 00:42:21.560
They can pretty much pack it
up and go home, because

00:42:21.560 --> 00:42:23.710
everyone's going to think
they're ridiculous, no one

00:42:23.710 --> 00:42:25.955
will believe what they say, and
it's a stupid idea anyway,

00:42:25.955 --> 00:42:28.960
is basically the gist of
this conversation.

00:42:28.960 --> 00:42:34.050
And in chemistry, just like in
any discipline, you have all

00:42:34.050 --> 00:42:36.880
types of scientists, but also
all types of personalities,

00:42:36.880 --> 00:42:39.850
and unfortunately Pauli had a
personality that was known

00:42:39.850 --> 00:42:42.280
for, first of all, being very
arrogant, but also the very

00:42:42.280 --> 00:42:45.160
unfortunate trait of taking
other people's scientific

00:42:45.160 --> 00:42:46.930
ideas as his own.

00:42:46.930 --> 00:42:50.330
And as the story goes, as
Goudsmit was leaving and the

00:42:50.330 --> 00:42:54.850
door with slamming, Wolfgang
Pauli was already writing down

00:42:54.850 --> 00:42:58.590
this idea into a scientific
paper of the idea of a fourth

00:42:58.590 --> 00:42:59.840
quantum number.

00:42:59.840 --> 00:43:03.150
And, in fact, he did make some
more strides, he was a

00:43:03.150 --> 00:43:06.440
brilliant thinker, maybe he put
it more articulately than

00:43:06.440 --> 00:43:09.490
those two younger scientists
could have. But now, it has

00:43:09.490 --> 00:43:11.660
come to light that they are the
ones that do get credit

00:43:11.660 --> 00:43:14.860
for first really coming up
with this idea of a spin

00:43:14.860 --> 00:43:17.600
quantum number, and it's
interesting to think about how

00:43:17.600 --> 00:43:21.120
the politics work in different
discoveries, as well as the

00:43:21.120 --> 00:43:22.160
discoveries themselves.

00:43:22.160 --> 00:43:24.550
You see that a lot with Nobel
prizes, there's usually a nice

00:43:24.550 --> 00:43:27.680
little scandal, a nice little
interesting story behind who

00:43:27.680 --> 00:43:33.070
else was responsible for the
Nobel Prize-worthy discovery.

00:43:33.070 --> 00:43:37.170
So, here, Pauli came out on top,
we say, and he's known

00:43:37.170 --> 00:43:40.770
for the Pauli exclusion
principle, which tells us that

00:43:40.770 --> 00:43:43.810
no two electrons in the same
atom can have the same four

00:43:43.810 --> 00:43:45.770
quantum numbers.

00:43:45.770 --> 00:43:49.330
So let's just think exactly
what this means, and that

00:43:49.330 --> 00:43:52.360
means that if we take away
function and we define it in

00:43:52.360 --> 00:43:57.930
terms of n, l and m sub l, what
we're defining here is

00:43:57.930 --> 00:44:03.180
the complete description
of an orbital.

00:44:03.180 --> 00:44:06.150
In contrast, if we're taking
the wave function and

00:44:06.150 --> 00:44:12.580
describing it in terms of n, l,
m sub l, and now also, the

00:44:12.580 --> 00:44:15.640
spin, what are we
describing here?

00:44:15.640 --> 00:44:16.450
An electron.

00:44:16.450 --> 00:44:20.580
So now we have the complete
description of an electron

00:44:20.580 --> 00:44:21.780
within an orbital.

00:44:21.780 --> 00:44:26.160
So, that's an important
distinction to make -- what

00:44:26.160 --> 00:44:28.930
three quantum numbers tell us,
versus what the fourth quantum

00:44:28.930 --> 00:44:32.390
number can fill in for us
in terms of information.

00:44:32.390 --> 00:44:35.420
So what that means is that we're
limited in any atom to

00:44:35.420 --> 00:44:38.860
having two electrons per
orbital, right, because for

00:44:38.860 --> 00:44:42.380
any orbital we can either have
a spin up electron, a spin

00:44:42.380 --> 00:44:44.670
down electron, or both.

00:44:44.670 --> 00:44:48.980
So, if we look at neon just as
an example, neon has ten

00:44:48.980 --> 00:44:53.100
electron in it, and once we
look at all the orbitals

00:44:53.100 --> 00:44:55.920
written out here, this is
probably a familiar thing for

00:44:55.920 --> 00:44:59.310
you to look at, but it's
important to think about why,

00:44:59.310 --> 00:45:02.600
in fact, we don't just put all
ten electrons, why wouldn't

00:45:02.600 --> 00:45:04.860
they just want to go in that
ground state, that lowest

00:45:04.860 --> 00:45:05.940
state, right?

00:45:05.940 --> 00:45:08.240
That should be the most stable,
the lowest energy

00:45:08.240 --> 00:45:11.060
orbital for it to be in, and the
reason they can't do that

00:45:11.060 --> 00:45:13.470
is because of the Pauli
exclusion principle -- the

00:45:13.470 --> 00:45:17.410
idea that all of the electrons
have to have a different set

00:45:17.410 --> 00:45:20.850
of four quantum numbers, so only
two of them can have the

00:45:20.850 --> 00:45:24.140
same set of three quantum
numbers here, because for m

00:45:24.140 --> 00:45:28.220
sub s, we're only left
with two options.

